{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 12:24:31.267004", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report\\n===============================\\nScope / context\\n- Topology: multi‑tier Clos using EBGP. Super‑spine AS65000 connects to both spines. Two pods with two spines and two leaves. Each leaf attaches one host:\\n  - pc_0_0 — 10.0.0.2/24 (via leaf_router_0_0: 10.0.0.1)\\n  - pc_0_1 — 10.0.1.2/24 (via leaf_router_0_1: 10.0.1.1)\\n- Inter‑router links: /31s in 172.16.0.0/16.\\n- Routing: FRR EBGP between leaves ↔ spines ↔ super‑spine.\\n\\nSummary / executive conclusion\\n- Network appears healthy. EBGP sessions are established; each leaf advertises its /24 and all routers have learned both host prefixes. Data‑plane connectivity between hosts is verified (ping successful, low latency, no packet loss).\\n- No BGP session flaps, no down interfaces, and no immediate misconfigurations or missing routes were observed from the collected data.\\n- Observations show multipath availability (multiple BGP paths) indicating redundancy is functioning.\\n\\nEvidence & detailed findings\\n1) Host reachability (data‑plane)\\n- pc_0_0 → pc_0_1: 2 tx, 2 rx, 0% loss, avg RTT ≈ 2.05 ms\\n- pc_0_1 → pc_0_0: 2 tx, 2 rx, 0% loss, avg RTT ≈ 2.41 ms\\n- Interpretation: bidirectional reachability is working with low latency and no packet loss.\\n\\n2) Interface status and addressing (control‑plane reachability)\\n- All router and host interfaces that are part of the topology are UP/LOWER_UP.\\n- Key IPs (examples):\\n  - leaf_router_0_0: eth2 10.0.0.1/24; eth0 172.16.0.5/31; eth1 172.16.0.9/31\\n  - leaf_router_0_1: eth2 10.0.1.1/24; eth0 172.16.0.7/31; eth1 172.16.0.11/31\\n  - spine_router_0_0: eth0 172.16.0.1/31; eth1 172.16.0.4/31; eth2 172.16.0.6/31\\n  - spine_router_0_1: eth0 172.16.0.3/31; eth1 172.16.0.8/31; eth2 172.16.0.10/31\\n  - super_spine_router_0: eth0 172.16.0.0/31; eth1 172.16.0.2/31\\n- No interface errors (RX/TX error counters = 0), no links administratively down.\\n\\n3) BGP configuration and adjacency\\n- FRR configs show intended EBGP neighbor relationships and AS numbers:\\n  - Leaves: AS 65200 (leaf 0_0) and 65201 (leaf 0_1) configured to peer with both spines (65100 & 65101).\\n  - Spines: AS 65100 (spine 0_0) and 65101 (spine 0_1) configured to peer to super‑spine AS 65000 and to both leaves.\\n  - Super‑spine: AS 65000 peers to both spines (172.16.0.1 and 172.16.0.3).\\n- BGP tables show the expected advertisements:\\n  - Each leaf advertises its connected /24 (leaf_router_0_0 => 10.0.0.0/24; leaf_router_0_1 => 10.0.1.0/24).\\n  - Spines and super‑spine have learned both /24s; multiple paths are visible (redundancy).\\n- Example BGP observations:\\n  - super_spine_router_0 sees 10.0.0/24 and 10.0.1/24 via both spines.\\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1 show routes to both host subnets via the leaves/spines as expected.\\n- No indications of prefix suppression, policy rejection, or BGP next‑hop failures in the snapshots provided.\\n\\n4) Routing table consistency\\n- Each leaf has the connected /24 installed (C) and the remote /24 learned via BGP (B) with valid next‑hop pointing into the spine network.\\n  - leaf_router_0_0 route for 10.0.1.0/24 → via 172.16.0.4 (spine 0_0)\\n  - leaf_router_0_1 route for 10.0.0.0/24 → via 172.16.0.6 (spine 0_0)\\n- Spines/super‑spine have BGP routes to both /24s and selected best paths; next‑hops are consistent with the topology.\\n\\nObservations / minor notes (not faults)\\n- Multipath visibility: BGP tables across devices show multiple alternative paths (expected in closet/fat‑tree). Best path selection varies by router, which can produce asymmetric forwarding for some flows — this is normal unless a policy enforces symmetry.\\n- Interface traffic counters: some hosts show skewed TX/RX totals (e.g., pc_0_0 TX >> RX). This is an observation of traffic pattern, not an error (could be application traffic direction). No errors or drops were reported on interfaces.\\n- No debug logs of BGP keepalive failures or update storms were presented; the FRR configs include debug statements but there are no traces of flapping in the data fetched.\\n\\nAnomalies / faults detected\\n- None detected from the provided data set. Specifically:\\n  - No down interfaces or administrative shutdowns.\\n  - No BGP session failures evidenced by missing routes — all expected prefixes are present everywhere.\\n  - Data‑plane testing (host pings) succeeded with low latency and no loss.\\n\\nLocalization / devices examined\\n- Devices inspected: pc_0_0, pc_0_1, leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0.\\n- All devices are operational and advertising/learning routes as designed.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis\\n- Since no anomaly was detected, there is no root cause to identify for a failure. The current state indicates correct topology configuration, BGP peering and route propagation, and functional data‑plane connectivity between hosts.\\n\\nRecommended next steps to deepen analysis (optional—no remediation)\\n- If you want deeper validation (not requested as remediation), useful additional checks would be:\\n  - show ip bgp summary (to confirm session states/uptimes/established neighbors)\\n  - show bgp neighbors detail (to check timers, hold time, and any path attributes)\\n  - capture tcpdump on leaf↔spine links to observe BGP OPEN/KEEPALIVE/UPDATE timing if intermittent issues suspected\\n  - run iperf between hosts to exercise throughput and detect hidden packet drops under load\\n  - if traffic asymmetry is a concern, run traceroutes (both directions) to show path symmetry\\n\\nConclusion\\n- Based on the collected interface, routing, and BGP configuration/state outputs and successful host reachability tests, the network is healthy and operating as designed. No anomalies, failures, or misconfigurations were identified in the provided dataset., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='cae7229a-89e7-46c0-9847-81a4fcf34f76'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
